H11   Sustentacular Cells and The Blood-Testis Barrier

The graphic shows a section from the wall of a seminiferous tubule; the lumen is at the top, the basement membrane (BM) below. Like any epithelium, germinal epithelium is avascular. The highly vascularized interstitial tissue is shown below the dense CT capsule. 
Sustentacular cells (S) extend from the BM to the lumen. Sperm develop in the paracellular space between adjacent sustentacular cells, each supporting 30-50 developing germ cells.
Picture 1
Rectangle 3

Sustentacular cells are joined by tight junctions (TJ), which form the blood-testis barrier. This separates two fluid compartments, the basal compartment (B) and the adluminal compartment (A).
Fluid in the basal compartment is confluent with the vascularized interstitial tissue and its WBCs.
The composition of the fluid in the adluminal compartment, testicular fluid, is tightly controlled by the sustentacular cells. The tight junctions prevent WBC transmigration from the basal compartment to the adluminal compartment, and thus keep the developing sperm hidden from immuno-surveillance. This is the blood-testis barrier.
Starting at puberty, FSH stimulates sustentacular cells to produce androgen-binding protein (ABP), which binds and concentrates the testosterone produced by interstitial cells. They also produce inhibin, which inhibits FSH release from the anterior pituitary.
